ce:section.ce:para:
Aquatic products are one of the foods most likely to be contaminated with CAP. Herein, shrimp, mackerel, and codfish were used to validate the practicability of the proposed aptasensor. Aquatic samples were spiked with CAP at various levels (0, 0.1, 2, 5, and 10 μg kg−1). Subsequently, CAP levels in these samples were measured in parallel using the aptasensor and LC–MS/MS, the standard method for detecting contaminants in food samples. The standard curve for CAP detection by LC–MS/MS is displayed in Fig. S7. The performance of the method for detecting CAP from the spiked samples was visualized by the heat-map in Fig. 5a. The consistency test revealed the aptasensor results were highly in agreement with those of the LC–MS/MS, with concordance correlation coefficient (CCC) of 0.996, 0.996, and 0.965 for shrimp, mackerel, and codfish, respectively (Fig. 5b–d). The Bland–Altman analysis also revealed high consistency between results obtained by the two approaches for 95 % confidence level (Fig. 5e–g). The corresponding data of spiking recovery and repeatability relative standard deviation (RSDr,
n = 3
) were shown in Table S3. By utilizing the aptasensor, our analytical method yields the recovery ranges of 79.6–107.4 % in shrimp, 101.8–120.4 % in mackerel, and 87.0–124.0 % in codfish. Relative standard deviation of repeatability (RSDr,
n = 3
) of the method for aquatic samples spiked with 0.1, 2, 5, and 10 μg kg−1 of CAP was 13.59 %, 2.48 %, 2.03 %, and 1.97 % at maximum values, respectively. The above results highlight the acceptable accuracy and reliability of the developed method for CAP detection in real aquatic products.
